A tour around our little holler tucked away in a small town in Tennessee. We have such rich history in our little holler and I’ll start with the old general store. It was the general store for this community in the early 1900’s and you can still see the old wood stove inside that would heat it in the winter months. Down the road is a grave marker. It’s the grave of Old Isham, the beloved horse of General Cheatham. He retired, after the war, here on a farm. Our house and land is made up of the old Cheatham farm. Across the road from our farm is the old cemetery. Inside you will find beautiful old grave stones with carvings and moss. One of a 29yr woman and her precious baby. Another marked with Mr. Patton an Irish immigrant who died at 60yrs of age in 1815. I love exploring history and can’t believe I live in a place surrounded by it!

Anyone else feel like their hand has been forced in so many ways over the last few years? 
.
Whether it’s where you live, how you school your kids, what you eat, if you had a certain thing put in your body to keep your job… the dang list goes on. And it’s forced so many of us into different lifestyles. Forces us to stretch and grow and be uncomfortable enough to take a stand and make a change and even look crazy in the process. 
.
The skills we’ve learned and the life we’ve lived over the last couple of years seems idyllic to some, insane to others, and a fad to many. The reality is, there’s a movement of families (and it seems many bold women are leading this movement and asking our husbands to trust us) that want to regain what was lost, what’s been withheld and marginalized. An entire way of life that brings so much fruit and so much FREEDOM. It brings opportunity and ingenuity and an position to pivot when circumstances change. It offers us a chance at grassroots ways of life that have sustained communities for generations on end and removed us from the perpetual cycle of being dependent on the people who would rather keep us sick and depressed and meandering through life from one thing to the next. 
.
You may not have ever dreamed of homesteading or farming like I did, but the reality is, your hand may be forced. So I say this without being laced with fear: what are you doing to get ready for that? 
.
I’m so grateful for @colonialfarmstead and her willingness to hear the call to a self succulent life when we both lived in crowded suburbs. Having a kindred spirit in this journey is an immeasurable gift. And I’m so grateful she’s generous enough to share her experience with all of us.

My time with my Dolly girl has ended. We have had much discussion on what we should do and this was right for our family. With my husband working on fixing his autoimmune issues we just wanted to have less stress in our lives. With Slash gone she had become more rowdy and was jumping our fence daily. For her safety and the safety of our neighbors we made the decision to hand her over to a great older farmer who will have better facilities for her. 

I don’t regret that we bought her at all. It was such a great experience and I wouldn’t change it! Dolly taught me so many things about myself. First, I never knew I could love an animal as much as I love her. She was the best. Second, I learned that I can do hard things. 

Dolly, we miss you so much and every time I pass that open gate I think of you!

To Billy on our 18 year wedding anniversary. 

We’ve been together twenty three years and married eighteen! How amazing! We met as teenagers and fell in love. Who says we were too young to know what love was. We knew and here we are. 

We have grown together as individuals and as a couple. We have seen each other at our worst and our best. We know each others deepest secrets and deepest pains. 

You are the one who I look forward to seeing all day. You are the one who makes me feel like the most beautiful woman in the room. You are the one who makes me laugh until I cry. You are the one who gave me my precious boys. You are the one who has healed my heart from abandonment as a child. You are the one who has showed me what a husband and father should be. And you are one of the greats. 

I’m so glad we got together as teenagers because that means I get to spend so much more time with you. Making memories and still growing as individuals and as a couple.  I can’t wait to grow old with you and sit on our porch and as we talk about our beautiful life we’ve built together. Hopefully with grandchildren on our lap! 

I love you so much! Happy anniversary! ❤️😘

Being preoccupied with trying to build and run a homestead and just life in general has kind of sucked the want and creativity right out of me. I started out on film many moons ago and it’s my favorite medium. I got a vintage 35mm Contax G2 for my anniversary and can’t wait to shoot with it and develop the film and show you guys. This was shot with my digital slr camera. I gravitate more towards moodier images so I like to underexpose my images a bit. I taught Liam how to shoot in all manual mode and he understood everything I said about F stops and shutter speed and ISO. I was SO impressed!

Older houses have always sparked something in me. I have always wanted to live in one…maybe someday. They have such a rich history and stories to tell. They were built with such craftsmanship that has been lost today. They were built to last and be passed down generation to generation. 

The boys and I toured Oaklands Mansion today and they got to practice taking pictures on the inside of a house. They took some amazing shots that I’ll share with you when I can download and look through all the images. It has been such a neat experience taking pictures with my boys and teaching them about photography. I’m getting my passion back for photography one shot at a time.

This is one of the beautiful bedrooms in the mansion. The home is in Murfreesboro if you are ever that way, you should check it out.

Spent the whole day with my bestie on my 42nd birthday! She took me to an authentic British tea house and we had high tea with all the wonderful British treats! The clotted cream was to die for. Get you a friend that isn’t afraid to tell you the truths you need to hear. One who you can laugh with and cry with. They are a rare gem. I had such a wonderful day today!

Noah officially got his drivers license and can now drive on his own without an adult. I’ll tell ya, my mommy heart is having a hard time with this one. He drove to Murfreesboro today with his cousin to hangout and Christmas shop and it’s just so weird. I swear he was just 3yrs old. How can this be?! When I look at his face, I still see that little 3yr old that needed me to kiss his bruises and would want me when he got hurt. I love that he’s growing into an incredible young man but it really hurts to let him go. This is such a weird stage of motherhood and I’m having a hard time with it.
